nsel for Bryan C.\nPerry. Signed on 10/7/2022 by Magistrate Judge Willie J. Epps, Jr.(Warren, Melissa) [2:22-mj-03027-WJE] (Entered: 10/07/2022)\n10/11/2022 5 Minute Entry for proceedings held before Magistrate Judge Willie J. Epps, Jr: INITIAL APPEARANCE as to Jonathan S. O'Dell held on\n10/11/2022. Defendant present, in custody, ready to proceed. The Federal Public Defender's Office has been appointed to represent\ndefendant and will assist defendant with filling out the Financial Affidavit (CJA 23 form) which will then be filed in ECF. Defendant\nadvised of the charges contained in the complaint and supporting affidavit, penalties faced if convicted, and his rights. The Court\nconfirmed the Government's obligations under Brady and its progeny, and advised of consequences for failing to abide by the same; order\nto follow. Government moves to detain. Preliminary Hearing and Detention Hearing scheduled for Thursday, October 13, 2022, at 1:30\npm. Defendant remanded to the custody of the US Marshal pending further order of this Court. Counsel appearing for USA: Michael\nOliver. Counsel appearing for Defendant: Katie Wang. Pretrial/Probation Officer: Lance Jordan. Time in court: 10:05 am to 10:12 am. To\norder a transcript of this hearing please contact Angel Geiser, 573-556-7564. This is a TEXT ONLY ENTRY. No document is attached.\n(Geiser, Angel) [2:22-mj-03026-WJE] (Entered: 10/11/2022)\n10/11/2022 ORAL ORDER as to Jonathan S. O'Dell. Pursuant to the Due Process Protections Act, the Court confirms the United States' obligation to\ndisclose to the defendant all exculpatory evidence--that is, evidence that favors the defendant or casts doubts on the United States' case--as\nrequired by Brady v. Maryland and its progeny, and orders the United States to do so. Failure to disclose exculpatory evidence in a timely\nmanner may result in consequences, including exclusion of evidence, adverse jury instructions, dismissal of charges, contempt\nproceedings, disciplinary acti